Thanks for the feedback! If your issue is related to the Flutter framework itself,
please open an issue at
[github.com/flutter/flutter](https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/new).

## Steps to Reproduce
Adding new code to make an HTTP call.
Had just added `import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;` and then started typing the line below.

```
Future<String> _backgroundJob(int dummy) async {
  print("starting backgroundJob");
  var client = http.C    // HERE.  Was typing this line when the Dart Analyzer error occurred
  while (true) {
    Future<http.Resposne>
    print("in backgroundJob");
    sleep(Duration(seconds: 10));
  }
  return "done";
}

```
I got the following error:

"
9:35 AM	Dart Analyzer Error
				Encountered a Dart Analysis Server error.
				Open issue submission form?
"

## Version info

Please paste the output of running `flutter doctor -v` here (available from the command
line or from `Tools > Flutter > Flutter Doctor`). It will provide the version of the
Flutter framework as well as of the IntelliJ plugin.

comment_data.body: @rtolar, was there an exception associated with the report?

I don't see an exception/stack trace of any kind, sorry.

The only thing it shows is:
"9:35 AM	Dart Analyzer Error
				Encountered a Dart Analysis Server error.
				Open issue submission form?
"

OK, ideally when you click on the `Open issue submission form` button, it should open a github issue web page pre-populated with some of the exception info, and a reference to a file with more complete information. If you're seeing that message in the IntelliJ log, it's probably lacking context to open the page correctly (it would work from the initial error message toast).

Clicking 'Open issue submission form' opened a browser with no URL populated.
e.g. blank page

@stevemessick, I think we've seen a few instances of the browser page being populated w/ incomplete info - it'd be worth investigating, to see if there are any URL encoding issues, or other places things might be going wrong.
/cc @pq @jwren as other good candidates. It will be a while before I have cycles for this.

> I think we've seen a few instances of the browser page being populated w/ incomplete info 

Since this seems the most actionable part of this, I'll rename the issue to track investigation.

Thanks @rtolar!

The problem is reproducible.
I created a skeleton app to reproduce:
https://github.com/rtolar/flutter_intellij_2611

Basically:
1) add dependency to http in pubspec.yaml:    http: ^0.11.3+17
2) add import in main.dart  `import 'package:http/http.dart' as http;`
3) start typing `var client = http.C`

I only get the error the first time I type that.
Restart Android Studio to get it to happen again.
Thanks for the repo! I think we should file a separate issue for that on the dart-lang/sdk repo - this issue can track not getting data consistently plumbed through the browser url.

When I reproduce this problem using the versions of Flutter and Dart as specified, I get a valid issue submission form (appended). The referenced file exists and has a full stack trace. It looks like a Windows problem so maybe a Windows hacker could take a look.
